issues.body:
### Issue

From what I've read, I was under the expectation that the repo map would contain a bit of a stencil of the project, function signatures, classes, etc, but I see entire function bodies. This very quickly overflows the size of the repo map and makes aider unable to discover much about the project, at least on my local setup.

If I put the following JS file into an empty git project:
```
function foo() {
  console.log(1, 2);
}
function bar() {
  console.log(3, 4);
}
function baz() {
  console.log(5, 6);
}
```

Then I run `aider --show-repo-map`, I see this:

```
test.js:
│function foo() {
⋮
│function bar() {
│  console.log(3, 4);
│}
│function baz() {
│  console.log(5, 6);
⋮
```

I have found that hacking the constructor to `TreeContext` to include `parent_context=False` as well as the existing `child_context=False` in `aider/repomap.py` makes it work as I would expect. After applying this hack, I see the following repo map instead:

```
test.js:
│function foo() {
⋮
│function bar() {
⋮
│function baz() {
⋮
```

I'm not sure if this is a bug or not, or if it's the intended behaviour, it just didn't seem right to me so I'm reporting it. The default behaviour makes working with even moderately sized projects blast past my repo map size with huge reams of implementation code, and aider is not able to make the LLM aware of much of these projects' surface area. It's particularly severe on Go projects, where implementations tend to be much less dense and much more spread out than python projects.

If it's not expected, I'm happy to submit a PR, I just wanted to confirm first.

### Version and model info

Aider v0.82.2
Model: ollama_chat/qwen2.5-coder:14b with whole edit format
Git repo: .git with 6 files
Repo-map: using 8192 tokens, auto refresh

